managing food price volatility approaches at the global national and household levels events at stanford managing food price volatility approaches at the global national and household levels facebook twitter email print add to calendar what does price instability have to do with food security price spikes hurt poor consumers price collapses hurt farmers and price risks reduce investment peter timmer thomas d cabot professor of development studies emeritus at harvard university suggests that food price instability also has a deeper and more insidious impact it slows down economic growth and the structural transformation that is the pathway out of rural poverty food price instability really hurts the poor in both the short run and the long run thom jayne professor of international development at michigan state university will join the conversation as a discussant following the main presentation when thursday may 26 2011 4 00 pm approximate duration of 2 hour s where bechtel conference center encina hall freeman spogli institute for international studies map audience faculty staff alumni friends general public students tags environment international conference symposium sponsor program on food security and the environment contact 650 723 4920 ashdean stanford edu admission admission is free and open to the public please rsvp by may 19 using the following link http foodsecurity stanford edu events registration 6553 permalink http events stanford edu events 273 27371 more info last modified may 16 2011
